More on Dependencies

This lesson continues the discussion on dependencies and the various mechanisms available to resolve conflicting versions of a dependency.

We'll cover the following
  • Dependency conflict resolution
    • Excluding transitive dependencies
  • Adding as a direct dependency
  • Dependency management
  • Optional dependencies

Dependency conflict resolution#

So, what happens when a project depends on two projects which in turn depend on different versions of the same project? How does Maven solve this conflict? Consider the following setup:

In the above setup, Project A depends on Project B and Project C. Both Project B and Project C in turn depend on the Google artifact for json parsing known as Gson. However, Project B depends on the newer version 2.8.6, while Project C depends on the older 1.7.2 version. Let’s do a hands-on exercise and see which version Maven picks.

In the example above, Maven ends up choosing the version 2.8.6 for the Gson dependency. If we draw a tree of dependencies starting with the POM of Project A as the root, Maven will choose the dependency nearest from the root in case of conflicting dependency versions. Let’s see the dependency tree of Project A as printed out by Maven.

A tree depiction is shown below:

Observe that both the dependencies are at the same level in the tree, in such situations Maven breaks the tie by choosing the dependency that occurs first in the tree. In our case, the tree printed on the console by Maven displays the dependency version 2.8.6 first and selects it. Determining what version of an artifact to choose when multiple versions are encountered as dependencies is known as dependency mediation. Maven uses the nearest-definition wins strategy.

If we change the order of the projects in the POM, i.e., place dependency for Project C before Project B then in the dependency tree, Project C and its transitive dependencies will be listed first. Maven will pick version 1.7.2 for Gson instead. The dependency tree for this change is shown below:

The tree depiction now looks like:

We can have Maven pick a desired version for a dependency if we don’t like the version Maven picks using its nearest wins strategy. Let’s explore the different ways we can achieve this.

Excluding transitive dependencies#

Say we don’t want the version 2.8.6 to be selected by Maven and we also don’t want to change the order in which the two dependencies appear in Project A’s POM file. In this scenario we can instruct Maven to not include the transitive dependency Gson version 2.8.6 using the <exclusions> tag as follows:

        <dependency>
            <groupId>io.datajek</groupId>
            <artifactId>project9-projectb</artifactId>
            <version>1</version>
            <exclusions>
                <exclusion>
                    <groupId>com.google.code.gson</groupId>
                    <artifactId>gson</artifactId>
                </exclusion>
            </exclusions>
        </dependency>

The above snippet tells Maven to not include the transitive Gson dependency version 2.8.6. The dependency tree now looks as follows:

Note, in the output above, Gson’s version 2.8.6 isn’t listed as a transitive dependency for Project B. Exclusions are set on a specific dependency in your POM, and are targeted at a specific groupId and artifactId.

Adding as a direct dependency#

Say we don’t want our project to use either version 2.8.6 or version 1.7.2, instead we want version 2.7 to be used. We can achieve that by adding the version 2.7 as a direct dependency to Project A. The dependency tree as printed out by Maven looks as follows:

The direct dependency version takes precedence over the transitive dependency version.

Dependency management#

Yet another way to make Maven pick the dependency version you desire is to use <dependencyManagement> element. The primary purpose of dependency management is to consolidate the versions for various artifacts in one place that can then be inherited by multiple projects making maintenance easier. However, a secondary purpose of dependency management is to control the versions of artifacts used in transitive dependencies. We can add the following snippet in Project A’s POM file so that version 2.7 of Gson is selected.

    <dependencyManagement>
        <dependencies>
            <dependency>
                <groupId>com.google.code.gson</groupId>
                <artifactId>gson</artifactId>
                <version>2.7</version>
            </dependency>
        </dependencies>
    </dependencyManagement>

The Maven dependency tree looks as follows. Note, it is different from the tree printed out for the other options we discussed.

Optional dependencies#

We can also mark the Gson dependencies in projects B and C as optional and add our own desired version in Project A’s POM. Marking a direct dependency as optional in a project’s POM excludes it as a transitive dependency for other projects. We’ll learn more about optional dependencies in an upcoming lesson. Though making dependencies optional isn’t intended for resolving version conflicts but is yet another, albeit, undesirable way to achieve that end.
